article.headline: Cash's double-double pace rout of Comets
article.linkText: Defending champion Shock end four-game losing streak
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Unlike Rasheed Wallace, Swin Cash
makes her guarantees in private.

That doesn't stop her from backing them up.

One day after guaranteeing a victory to her coach and teammates,
the All-Star had 19 points and 11 rebounds and the Detroit Shock
ended a four-game losing streak with an 82-63 victory over the
Houston Comets on Tuesday night.

"I remembered Rasheed's guarantee in the playoffs, so when we
got to practice on Monday, I told everyone that we would not lose
this game," she said. "I'm just glad my teammates were with me on
it."

Cash, playing on a sprained ankle, came close to the third
triple-double in WNBA history. She had eight assists and six steals
as Detroit beat Houston for the first time in 10 tries.

"That was a great game for Swin and a great game for our
team," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "She's playing on a bum
ankle, but that's Swin. She's going to fight through anything."

Wallace guaranteed the Pistons would win Game 2 of the Eastern
Conference finals against the Indiana Pacers. They did win to even
the series and Detroit went on to win the NBA title.

Ruth Riley and Cheryl Ford, who were both left off the Olympic
team coached by Houston's Van Chancellor, each scored 16 points.

"That didn't have anything to do with tonight," Riley said.
"I'm focused on the Shock right now, not the Olympics. I've got
four years to convince the committee next time."

Michelle Snow had 13 points and 14 rebounds for Houston which
lost its third straight. Tiffani Johnson added 12 points for the
Comets, and Sheryl Swoopes had 10.

"We just couldn't get the momentum going our way," Johnson
said. "We could get it down to maybe nine or eight, but then
something would happen. We would give up an offensive board or turn
the ball over."

Detroit led 43-33 at halftime despite shooting just 36.6
percent. The Shock outrebounded the Comets 25-17, including 12-3 on
the offensive end.

Houston cut the gap to seven points early in the second half,
but Detroit responded with an 8-2 run to make it 53-40. The Comets
never got closer than 10 points thereafter, and Chancellor was
ejected after picking up two late technical fouls for arguing.

"Give Detroit credit -- they needed a win and they ran the
ball," Chancellor said. "They hammered us more than any team has
ever hammered us on the boards."

After the game, Laimbeer criticized Chancellor for his public
rebukes of starting guards Kedra Holland-Corn and Sheila Lambert.
Both players were with Detroit last season, and received their
championship rings in a pregame ceremony.

"He's kind of losing his brain these days," Laimbeer said.
"But what disturbs me is the way he treats his guards -- calling
them out in the paper every day and jerking them out of games. I
don't approve of that."
